description.value: Limestone false-door and architrave of Ptahshepses: the architrave, which is carved in fine, detailed, sunk relief, contains five lines of text consisting of standard invocation-formulae to Osiris and Anubis. The false door consists of the false door proper with two lines of text on each side containing the titles of Ptahshepses, flanked on both sides by panelled walls carrying the biographical inscription of Ptahshepses in which he describes his birth in the time of Mycerinus, his marriage to Khamaat, a princess and daughter, probably, of Shepseskaf, and his career under four further kings, continuing down, probably, to Nyuserre of the Fifth Dynasty. All the texts on the false door are carved in good sunk relief, very sharply cut. On each side of the door is a long panel bearing representations of food-offerings, carved in fine low relief. The architrave is complete and in good condition. The false door is generally in good condition apart from a few small places where the surface is rubbed. The false door was painted a mottled pink to simulate granite and most of this colour remains. The hieroglyphs were painted green. On the side panels many of the vessels and parts of other objects were painted red; traces of green remain on some of the vegetables and floral offerings. No other colour can now be discerned. There is no colour on the architrave.

description.value: Limestone stela of Amenemwia: a round-topped stela divided into three registers with figures in sunk relief and incised texts. In the upper register the commander of the 'mškbyw' of the ship's contingent Ramses III, beloved of Sekhmet, Amenemwia, called K?r, kneels on the right in adoration of Osiris who is enthroned in the centre and behind whom stand Horus and Isis. In the second register two women and one man kneel in an attitude of worship: the lady of the house and chantress of Pre?, T?-bw-b?, his mother, the chantress of the lady of the sycamore, Mwt-m-w??, and his paternal grandfather, the keeper of secrets of the temple of Ra, 'ln?r(t)-n?t . In the third register four men stand in adoration: his father, the ?t n?r priest and keeper of secrets of the temple of Merenptah in the temple of Ra, ?wy, his brother, the first charioteer of His Majesty, P?-R?-m-?b, his brother, the King's Son (?), My, and his brother, the w?b-priest of the temple of Ra-Horakhty, P?-?ww. description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela of Besenmut: this round-topped stela is divided into three sections. At the top is a curved sky-sign above a winged sun-disk with pendent uraei. The top and middle registers are divided by a multi-coloured border. The middle register comprises two scenes back to back under a sky-sign. On the right Besenmut in a leopard-skin over a white skirt adores Ra-Horakhty, who stands behind an altar on which rests a water-pot cooled by a lotus-blossom. On the left the deceased adores Atum who stands behind a similar altar. The third section of the stela consists of six lines of text divided in the middle into a prayer to Ra-Harakhty on the right and a prayer to Atum on the left on behalf of the prophet of Montu, Besenmut, son of the prophet of Montu Ns-p?-sfy and the lady 'Irty-rw. The stela is cracked part way down the front and damaged on the top left side. The edges are chipped with loss to some text. The background of the stela is white. The sky-sign at the top is blue. The disk is red with pink uraei who have blue heads and a red and white crown edged in black respectively. The upper wings are blue with a pink patch streaked in blue; while the lower wings are green edged in red. The hieroglyphs are blue and red. There is a large multicoloured border consisting of green, pink, blue, and red rectangles separated by two white and one black stripe and edged in green. In the middle register the sky-sign is blue and the hieroglyphs are black on a pink background separated by blue lines. The human figures have a red body, black eye on white, blue wig with red cone and fillet, white kilt with black edges and details and green belt, green collar, and pink leopard-skin with black dots. The altars and pots are pink, edged in black. The lotuses have green stems, pink bases, and green, blue, and white flowers. The gods have red bodies, white kilts, green upper garments, collars, and sceptres, black ankh-signs, brown belts, and black and green tails. The face of Ra-Horakhty is white with black features and green outer eye. His wig is blue, and his disk red with a green uraeus. Atum has a red face with black beard, black eye on white, and red and white crown. The hieroglyphs at the bottom are black on the white background between blue lines. The two texts are separated by a black vertical line down the centre. The back and sides have been plastered.

Behind them is Imhotep, an anthropoid deity wearing a cap and carrying a was scepter and ankh sign. A large 'was', combined with 'ankh' and 'djed' signs, forms a border along each edge. The inscription below has two sections, the upper lines carved in hieroglyphs and the lower lines with the same information painted in demotic script. description.value: Round-topped limestone stela, from the tomb of Horemheb at Saqqara: winged sun-disc with pendant uraei; relief representation of Horemheb, standing with arms uplifted in adoration, before Ra-Horakhty, Thoth and Maat with remains of fifteen columns of hieroglyphs; twenty-five registers of hieroglyphs containing a prayer to Ra; traces of red, blue and yellow paint are visible.    Round-topped limestone stela of Horemheb: in the arch, carved in low relief, is the winged disc with pendent uraei. The stela is divided into two registers. The first register comprises a scene carved in low relief. The deceased stands with arms uplifted in an attitude of adoration before the deities Ra-Horakhty, Thoth and Maat, who stand on pedestals. The deceased is clad as in the foregoing panels, but without uraeus or fan and wearing a bead collar. In front of and behind him is an incised text in four vertical columns. Ra-Horakhty, whose pedestal is in the shape of a hieroglyphic sign, is falcon-headed and wears a long braided wig surmounted by a disk with uraeus, a bead collar and a short garment reaching to the knees, with tail. He holds an 'ankh' in the right hand and a sceptre in the left. Above him is text incised in five vertical columns. Thoth, who is ibis-headed, is attired like Ra-Horakhty, and also holds an 'ankh' in the right hand and a sceptre  in the left. Above him is incised a text, in three vertical columns. Maat, who is human-headed, wears a long braided wig surmounted by a fillet and a feather, and a long tight-fitting dress reaching to the ankles. She holds an 'ankh' in the right hand and a sceptre  in the left. Above her is a text, incised in three vertical columns. The second register comprises an inscription, incised in twenty-five horizontal lines. The upper portion of the stele is considerably mutilated and small abrasions have occurred at the edges. Some superficial cracks are visible, but otherwise the text is in an excellent state of preservation. The bodies of the males, the disc of Horakhty, the dress and fillet of Maat bear considerable traces of red paint. Yellow is visible in many of the hieroglyphs and some bright blue remains at the edges.

description.value: One half of a limestone stela (the other half is EA 1988), with incised Coptic texts on both sides.    One side (here called A) bears the upper eight lines of a long text (EA 1988 bears the following ten lines). The other side (here called B) bears a shorter text of two lines.     The two texts are evidently of a different date; one is upside down in relation to the other.    One of the narrow sides bears remains of decorative reliefwork, which shows that the slab was extracted from a larger architectural element. If either inscription (side A or B) is viewed the right way up, the narrow decorated side is to its right.

In the middle register the deceased stands on the right in adoration of Osiris, Hapy (?), and Imsety. Below are four lines of text. The stela is in a poor state of preservation. The surface is badly cracked and worn, so much of the decoration is lost or faded. At the top the black edges of the wing and uraeus on the right survive. It appears that the upper wing was green and the middle wing red, and this section had a red lower border. The human figure in the middle has a red body and apparently a white garment edged in black. The bodies of the gods are red, but only the black outlines of the faces remain, apart from that of Osiris which appears to be green. The texts are black between red lines, but are largely illegible. There appears to have been a red border around the stela and the sides.

description.value: Rectangular sycomore fig wood stela of Merirtyfy: the panel is divided into two sections. At the top is the barque of Sokar with four lines of hieratic written on the left. The main part of the stela depicts the deceased before two piles of offerings. Offerings of meat and fowl are shown on the left and bread and beer at the top on the right. Below these on the right are three columns of hieratic consisting of a prayer to Osiris on behalf of Merirtyfy. The panel has been covered with white gesso and the figures and texts outlined in black. In the upper section, the back of Sokar and the tops of the prow and stern of his boat are green, while its oars and poles are red. The wig of the deceased is blue and she wears green bracelets and carries a green staff. The haunch and ox head have red patches and red blood spurts from some of the offerings. The bread and beer are green. The panel is cracked in places and the texts and outlines are faded. Two small holes have been drilled near the top. The back and sides are also plastered.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela : this round-topped stela originally contained one scene. At the top appears to have been a curved sky-sign beneath which was a sun-disk with uraei. On either side of the disk is an 'wedjat'-eye and beneath the disk are some traces of signs which appear to read the 'Behdetite'. On the right stood a woman with her arms raised in adoration. In the centre was an altar piled with offerings above which were at least three columns of text, now lost. On the left stood the god Ra-Horakhty. The stela is in a poor state of preservation. The scene is nearly effaced and plaster has been lost in several places. The background appears to have been white. The disk, the dress and fillet of the lady, and part of the offerings are red. The face and kilt of the god are white, the beak black and the wig blue with black stripes. The wig of the lady is black. The signs under the disk are red, as may have been the hieroglyphs elsewhere, but these are now effaced. The plaster remains on the back and sides of the stela.

description.value: Grey glazed composition stela of Paser: the figures and text which appear on both sides of this stela are deeply cut and inlaid with white glaze. The feet and lower part of a 'was'-sceptre of a standing god are preserved on the left of one side facing the lower part of a standing figure in a long kilt, probably the god Amun being adored by Paser. Below the figures is a text which gives the name and titles of Paser. On the other side of this piece the figure of an official, doubtless Paser, appears on the left, and three columns of text on the right contain the name and titles of Paser, as does a horizontal line of text at the bottom. Only the lower portion of this piece is intact, and parts of the surface and inlaid glaze have been lost. The white inlay that remains has gone brown in places.

description.value: Limestone stela of Ramses II: this stela consists of six horizontal lines of incised text surmounted by a scene of which the lower parts of three figures in sunk relief remain. The figure of the king on the left stands with raised arms offering wine before Amun-Ra in the centre. Behind the god on the right stands a goddess who clasps the god with one hand. The text outlines certain endowments which the king made for the gods which favoured him. The stela is broken at the top and along the right side with loss to the scene and the main text. There is also a large gouge through the first three lines of text. The left edge has been restored in modern times. There are no traces of colour.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela of Neshor: this round-topped stela consists of an upper register with two separate scenes and below five lines of text. At the top of the stela is a winged sun-disk with uraei. In the scene on the right of the upper register the deceased, Neshor, on the right worships Ra-Horakhty, while in a similar scene on the left he worships Atum. The text in the second register contains a prayer to Osiris on behalf of Neshor, son of Psšt and the lady Gbtyw. The stela is well preserved apart from a few cracks. The background is sandy white. There is a multi-coloured border of yellow, blue, red, and green rectangles separated by one black and two white stripes edged in black around the stela and between the registers and the scenes in the upper register. The sun-disk is red with yellow uraei. The tripartite wings are yellow with blue dots and a blue upper edge, blue stripes on the background, and black stripes edged in black. The human figure is red with a blue collar and kilt outlined in black on the background. Ra-Horakhty has a blue body, green sceptre, yellow upper garment, red disk with black uraeus and sandy white face and kilt outlined in black. Atum has a red body, blue collar, green sceptre, red and white crown with green curl, blue and sandy white kilt outlined in black. The text here and in the lower register is black. The background of the lines in the lower register is alternatively brown and sandy white between black lines. The back and sides are plastered.

description.value: Limestone stela of Wentawat: this round-topped stela with slightly sloping sides is divided into two registers of scenes carved in sunk relief accompanied by incised texts and below them four horizontal lines of text. In the upper register Osiris is depicted in the centre seated on a throne, and behind him stand ?r-n?.?t.f, whose name is strangely written, and Isis, each with one arm raised. In front of Osiris are two altars, each bearing a water-pot cooled by a lotus-flower. On the right stands the first prophet of Amun of Ramses and viceroy of Kush, Wentawat, with his arms raised in adoration. The second register shows six people, five adults and one child, in an attitude of worship: the lady of the house and chantress of Wepwawet, T?-wsr(t), her [son], the stable-master of the Residence, N?-?r-?r, his brother, the first prophet of Amun of Ramses,  'lmn-w??-sw,  his  sister,  the chantress  of Wepwawet,  ?st ,  his  sister  the chantress of Wepwawet, T?-??y, and a child, T?-wsr(t), whose relationship to the others is lost. At the bottom of the stela the incised text contains a prayer to Osiris, Isis and Horus on behalf of the stable-master of the Residence, Naherher, and his father, the first prophet of  Amun of Ramses, Wentawat. This stela is in a poor state of preservation and much worn. Part of the last line has been lost subsequent to the taking of the photograph used here. There are traces of red paint on the hands and face of the lady Tausret.

description.value: Limestone funerary stela with a reclining woman: there is some loss to the surface of the stela, and any trace of paint has now vanished. Otherwise the stone is well preserved but for the subject's damaged right eye.    A woman dressed in a tunic and mantle, the latter draped over her hips, rests on three cushions piled onto a bed. She sits up, her face turned to the viewer. In her outstretched right hand she holds a libation dish ('patera'); in her left, a scroll. On her right wrist is a thick bracelet. Her hair is parted centrally, and arranged in tiers of curls with long locks falling behind the ears and onto the shoulders. The face is oval, the surviving proper left eye almond-shaped. The drapery is carefully carved to suggest a voluptuous figure.    Beside the woman on a shelf is a reclining jackal, representing the god Anubis, companion and protector of the dead. The bed and shelf are set within an architectural frame, perhaps representing the tomb. The setting comprises monolithic column shafts, set on bases which rest on rectangular plinths; lotus capitals with imposts; and an epistyle with moulded cornice supporting a moulded pediment.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela of Sehemmut (?): this round-topped stela is divided into three registers. The upper register has a winged sun-disk with uraei. In the second register the deceased female stands on the right with arms raised in adoration before an altar on which rests a lotus. Behind it stand Ra-Horakhty and the four sons of Horus. There are four lines of text at the bottom. The stela is poorly preserved. The wood is blackened and cracked, rendering many features indistinguishable. The registers were separated by  multi-coloured  borders  of which  only  the  red rectangles and the black and white stripes are now clear. The sun-disk was red and the lower wings and uraei were green or yellow. The female figure apparently had a red dress. The hieroglyphs at the bottom are black. The right edge had been broken off, but is now rejoined to the stela.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela (paint on plaster) depicting Nestjerenmaat: the lady of the house and chief chantress of Montu, lord of Thebes, Nestjerenmaat, daughter of the overseer of works of the estate of Amun, ?n?-p?-?rd and T?-špt, stands on the right of this round-topped stela with her hands raised in adoration of Ra-Horakhty who is standing on the left with a was-sceptre in one hand and an ankh-sign in the other. A row of 'ankh'- and 'was'-signs runs from the uraeus on the god's sun-disk to the nose of the lady. An altar heaped with offerings lies between the two figures. Above the altar and the lady are six columns of principal text plus three additional columns consisting of the usual funerary invocation. At the top of the stela is a winged sun-disk below a curved sky-sign. The colour has faded and the stela has suffered slight damage from flaking since its discovery. The sky at the top is blue. The side borders are brown with horizontal black stripes, while the bottom is red with green plants, now faded. The disk at the top is red with a white outer ring and brown uraei with blue heads. Its upper wings are white with brown dots; there is a thick blue stripe in the centre; and the lower wings are green with black lines and edged in red. The background of the stela is white. The hieroglyphs are black on a brown background between grey columns. The disk of the god is red with a white outer ring and a brown uraeus. His body is blue with a brown and blue upper face and a white lower face and black upper beak. The upper part of his costume is green now faded, and his kilt is brown and white. His necklace and bangles are brown. His sceptre is green and his ankh-sign is blue. The signs to the lady are black with brown centres. The altar is blue with green floral offerings, red and green lotuses, and red duck on a white dish on a black stand. The female figure has a pink body, darkened to red under the dress, a black wig with red fillet, red and white cone, and green wreath. The eye is black surrounded by white. The necklace is green, while the dress is white with pink stripes.

In the upper register on the left the foreman Paneb is kneeling with arms raised in adoration before a coiled serpent on the right, doubtless the goddess Meresger. description.value: Limestone stela of Naya: a round-topped stela divided into three registers. All figures are in sunk relief and all texts are incised. In the upper register the first stable-master of the lord of the two lands and royal messenger to every land, Naya, is kneeling on the right in adoration of Osiris who is seated in the centre and behind whom stand Isis, Horus and Khnum. In front of Osiris lies an altar on which rests a water-pot cooled by a lotus-blossom. In the second register the stable-master Naya stands beside a heap of offerings and is pouring a libation and offering incense to six figures squatting on the ground: his father, the overseer of horses, P?y, his mother, the lady of the house and chantress of Khnum, ?š?t-nbw, his sister, the lady of the house and chantress of Khnum, Ty, his son, the w?b-priest of Khnum, P(?)-n-T?-wr(t), his sister, the chantress of Khnum, Wrt-nfrt, and his sister, the chantress of Khnum, B?kt??. In the third register Naya is shown making similar offerings before seven squatting individuals: his father (doubtless grandfather), the overseer of the cattle of Amun, N?y?, his sister, the lady of the house and chantress of Khnum,  Wr(t)-nfrt (Naya the elder's wife and Naya the younger's grandmother), the chantress of Khnum, ?ry, the chantress of Khnum, Nbt-wnw, his sister, the chantress of Khnum, ?st, the w?b-priest and temple-scribe of Khnum, P?-sr and the porter of ... P?-sr, whose title is obscure but may refer to some type of shrine or ritual object. The stela is in a good state of preservation. In places the text and figures have been carved directly over the imperfections in the stone with no attempt being made to smooth the surface. There are no traces of colour.

description.value: Quartzite stela of Imiseba: a round-topped stela decorated on both sides with scenes in sunk relief and incised texts. Each side is divided into two registers. In the upper register of one side Imiseba, the w?b-priest before Thoth, god's father, and deputy in the temple of Thoth, is shown on the left offering incense and pouring a libation over an altar covered with offerings before Osiris who stands on the right. In the lower register there is a prayer to Osiris on behalf of Imiseba made by his son, the god's father of Thoth, P(?)-n-??wty. A male figure, presumably this son, is depicted on the left kneeling with his arms raised in worship. In the upper register on the other side Imiseba stands on the right holding a censer and pouring a libation over an altar covered with offerings before Thoth who stands on the left. In the lower register there is a prayer to Thoth, lord of Hermopolis, on behalf of the chantress of Thoth, Nfrt-?ry, made by her son, the god's father of Thoth and deputy in the temple of Thoth, Pendjehuty. The lady is depicted kneeling on the right with arms raised and a sistrum in one hand. The stela is in good condition apart from some wear to one surface which makes some signs difficult to distinguish. The surface is pitted with small holes. There are no traces of colour.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela of Djedmontuiufankh: the scene in the upper part of this round-topped stela is bordered by a sky-sign at the top and a column of text on each side. Djedmontiufankh kneels on the right in adoration of Ra-Harakhty who is seated on the left. Between them is an altar on which rests a water-pot cooled by a lotus-flower and flanked by two plants. Above the figures are eight columns of text and below eight lines of text with a prayer on behalf of Djedmonthefankh, son of ??m-?r. The stela is cracked in several places and appears to have been repaired in modern times. The background to the upper scene and the lower border are yellow. The sky-sign is blue with the columns of text on each side in black. The other hieroglyphs are outlined in black on white and filled in with blue paint, now faded, in many cases divided by blue lines. The human figure is red with white garment, and green belt and collar. The god has a red disk with black uraeus and wig, green face, blue body, red upper garment, white collar and kilt, black 'ankh', and green sceptre. The throne is blue and red divided by white with a red back and blue base. The altar is blue and white with a blue pot and lotus. The other plants are green. The edges of the stela are painted yellow and the back is plastered.

description.value: Limestone stela of Iimtapet: a small round-topped stela divided into two registers with incised texts and figures in sunk relief. In the upper register the goddess Meresger is shown in the form of a coiled serpent with a plumed headdress before an altar on which rests a water-pot cooled by a lotus-blossom. In the lower register the lady Iiemtapet kneels with her arms raised in adoration. The stela is well preserved apart from some damage along the edges. Traces of blue paint remain on the altar, while some red paint is visible in the border between the two registers and on the disk in the headdress of the goddess. There is black paint on the body of the serpent and on some hieroglyphs.

description.value: Limestone stela of Hormin: a small round-topped stela consisting of two registers with incised texts and figures in sunk relief. In the upper register Thoth, lord of Hermopolis, stands on the right before an altar on which rests a water-pot cooled by a lotus-flower. Amun-Ra, lord of the thrones of the two lands and foremost of Ipet-Sut, is seated on a throne in the centre and behind him stand Mut and Khons. In the lower register the w?b-priest and temple-scribe Hormin is kneeling on the right in adoration before a statue of Ramses II, named Re?-of-the-rulers. The lower right-hand corner of the stela has been broken off but later rejoined with slight loss. Otherwise the stela is well preserved, apart from a chip near the top and some wear in the centre. Traces of red paint remain on the body and legs of Thoth and the body of Hormin, and some black paint is visible on the face and beard of Khons and on some of the hieroglyphs.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela Bastetirdis(?): this round-topped stela is divided into three registers. At the top is a winged sun-disk without uraei. In the second register there is a scene under a sky-sign. The deceased stands on the right in adoration before an altar on which rests a lotus-flower. Behind it stand Ra-Horakhty, a winged Isis enfolding a šn-sign, and the four sons of Horus. Below are three lines of text containing a prayer to Ra-Horakhty on behalf of Bastetirdis(?), daughter of P?y.f-??w-?wy-B?stt. The stela has two large cracks down its face along the edges of the three planks of wood which form it. The stela is bordered on all sides and between registers by multi-coloured rectangles of red, blue, pink, and green separated by one black and two white  stripes  edged in black.  The  background  is yellow-white. The disk is red with black-dotted white upper wings which have a black upper edge, blue middle wings, and green lower feathers edged in red. The text in the upper register is black with a blue border. In the second register the sky is blue with black dots. The deceased has a brown body, white dress edged in black, and black wig. The altar is blue and the flower green. Ra-Horakhty has a red disk, white face with black features, blue wig, brown black-striped collar, green body and sceptre, and red hands. Isis has a green body, blue wig and head-dress, and red dress. Her outer right wing has a green upper edge, white patch with black dots, blue with red edge, green with black stripes, and finally blue edged in red. The inner left wing has a green upper and red lower left patch with black details and a blue right edge. The šn-sign is green with a red centre. The four gods have green bodies and sceptres, brown black-striped collars, and blue wigs. The faces of the first two are red, the third black, and the fourth white with black features. The hieroglyphs are black with blue dividing lines here and in the third register. The back and sides were plastered, now mostly worn away.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela of Ikhonsshedef: at the top of this round-topped stela appear a curved sky-sign and a winged sun-disk. The deceased stands on the right with his hands raised in adoration before an altar of offerings. Behind it stand Ra-Horakhty and Isis. The texts above the figures name the prophet of Amun, Nht.f-Mwt, Ra-Horakhty, and Mut (sic). The scene is bordered by a 'was'-sceptre on each side. Below the scene are three lines of text which contain a prayer on behalf of the ?t-n?r priest of Amun, Ikhonsushedef son of the fourth prophet of Amun, Nakhtefmut. Apart from slight cracks on the surface and slight damage along the edges, the stela is well preserved. The background of the stela is buff-white with a blue sky-sign at the top. The sun-disk is red with green uraei. Its upper wings are buff with black dots and a blue-green upper edge; while the lower wings are blue-green with feathers indicated in black and edged in red. The human figure has a red body with black features, a blue cap, green cone and collar, and blue-green kilt. The altar is blue-green with red and blue-green offerings. The god has a white face with black features, blue wig, red fillet, white crown, with blue-green feathers, green shoulder, red body, and green hands and sceptre. The goddess has a blue-green body and head-dress, red dress and fillet, blue wig, and black features, and holds a red and blue-green flower. The sceptres are green. The hieroglyphs are black on the buff background divided by blue lines. The sides and back of the stela are plastered.

description.value: Limestone stela of Mehu: the stela is in the form of a doorway with a cavetto cornice and torus-moulding. A prayer is inscribed on each side of the upper lintel continuing down the jambs-the one on the left to Osiris and the one on the right to Anubis, both on behalf of the overseer of the portal Mehu. There are two scenes in sunk relief on the central area of the doorway. The upper scene depicts Osiris enthroned in a shrine on the left behind an altar of offerings. He is being worshipped on the right side by Mehu and a royal prince with a sidelock holding a floral offering. The name of the prince is largely illegible, apparently Mry-'Imn(?)-p?y...(?). In the lower scene Mehu is seated on the left with the king's daughter Nebuemtekh and the lady Baket. Before them is an altar heaped with offerings. On the right his daughter Mutakhet pours a libation over the altar. The stela is much battered along the edges. The upper scene is very worn and discoloured in places. The upper edge on the right side of the scene is so damaged that the hieroglyphs are barely visible. There are two drilled holes, one on the right and the other on the left of the underside of the lintel, and corresponding holes on the upper surface of the base. These were not drilled very deep in the stone and possibly were intended as supports for wooden doors.

description.value: Granodiorite stela of Hor and Suty: a round-topped stela, carved within the rectangular framework of the door. The inscriptions throughout are incised and the figures carved in sunk relief. On the lintel of the door are three horizontal lines of text reading from the centre outwards. On the right side, there are three vertical lines of text. At the base of the right panel above a figure of Hor, seated at a table of offerings (almost entireley obliterated), are four (?) vertical lines of text. On the left side are three vertical lines of text. At the base of the left panel above a figure of Suty, seated at a table of offerings (almost entirely obliterated), are four vertical lines of text. On the right and left of the top of the arch of the stela itself, in the angle formed by the frame of the door is a 'wedjat'-eye. In the arch of the stela is a winged disc. The stela comprisies two registers. The first register is divided into two symmetrical scenes: On the right Anubis, shown with jackal's head, wearing a short skirt and holding a sceptre in the left hand and 'ankh' in the right, is adored by Hor and a woman (both almost entirely obliterated). Above Anubis, there are two vertical columns of text. Above Hor and the woman, are four vertical columns of text. On the left Osiris, shown in mummy form, wearing a crown, beard, necklace and counterpoise, and holding a sceptre in his hands, is adored by Suty and a woman (both obliterated). Above Osiris are two vertical columns of text. Above Suty and the woman, are four vertical columns of text. The second register carries an inscription in twenty-one horizontal lines. The stela is well preserved, but there are minor abrasions. The name of Suty in the left hand panel of the door and all the figures with their accompanying inscriptions, apart from those of the gods, were erased in antiquity.

description.value: Limestone stela of Qenhikhepeshef: a round-topped stela divided into two sections by a horizontal strip which is largely blank. The upper register bears a scene in sunk relief. The goddess Hathor is seated on a throne before an altar covered with offerings. Behind her stands a personified 'ankh'-symbol holding up a fan. An invocation to Hathor, Amun-Ra and Mut is incised in six columns. In a further column on the right the name of the owner's mother, N?wt-n?t is inscribed. On the left side of the horizontal dividing strip the names of the owner's sons, Nbt-st? and 'lmn-(m)-?b, are incised. The main body of the stela consists of a prayer to Hathor by the workman Qenhikhepeshef, son of the workman ??-(m)-nwn in twelve columns of incised text. He names his wife, the lady of the house, T?-nfrt, and his sons 'Imn-n?t and K?-(m)-pr-Pt?. The  figure  of Qenhikhepeshef kneeling with arms raised in an attitude of worship is carved in raised relief at the bottom right of the stela. Part of his wig is depicted under his chin. On the left of the figure the name of his daughter N?wt-n?t is incised. The text of this stela exhibits a number of errors in spelling and placement of signs. The stela is in a good state of preservation apart from some damage on the edges. There are no traces of colour.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela of Nehemesratawy: there are four sections on this round-topped stela, each of which is bounded by a multi-coloured border. At the top is a winged sun-disk with uraei which enfold a 'kheper'-beetle. On each side is a recumbent jackal. In the second register is a kheker-frieze. At the top of the third section is a sky-sign below which a scene is depicted. The deceased stands in adoration on the extreme right before an altar. Behind it stand Ra-Horakhty, a winged Isis enfolding a šn-sign, and three (Imsety, Hapy, and Duamutef) of the four sons of Horus. Three lines in the fourth section consist of a prayer to Ra-Horakhty on behalf of the deceased  ... rattawy, whose name is partially lost but is presumably the common Nehemesratawy, born of a parent whose name is not intelligible. The stela is composed of three planks which have cracked apart. The surface is much worn and the texts are badly faded in parts. The multi-coloured border is composed of red, blue, white, and green rectangles separated by one black and two white stripes, all edged in black. The general background of the stela is white. The disk is red with red uraei, one with a white and the other a red crown. The wings of the disk are divided into three parts: white with black dots and edges, green or yellow, and blue edged in red. The beetle and jackals are black and much faded. The 'kheker'-frieze is blue with red ties. The sky-sign is blue. The deceased has a red body, black wig, and white gown edged in black. The altar is blue. Ra-Horakhty has a green body, red hands and disk, blue (?) wig, white face with black features, and green sceptre. Isis has a green body, red dress and fillet, black wig, and blue head-dress. Her outer wing is divided into four bands, the upper edged in black and the others in red. The colours of the first three are unclear, possibly green, blue, green, and then definitely blue. Her inner wing is divided into three sections: blue with a red centre, red stripes on white on the lower edge, and black stripes on white on the outer end. The šn-sign has a red centre, and yellow or green outer ring edged in black. Imsety has a red body and black wig. Hapy has a red face, blue wig, yellow collar, and green body, while Duamutef has a red body, yellow collar, and black face. The texts are black between red and blue lines. The back, sides, and bottom appear to have been plastered.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela depicting Djedbastetiusankh: this small round-topped stela consists of one scene and a line of text below. The scene is bordered at the top by a curved sky-sign and on each side by the standards of the West (on the left) and presumably of the East (on the right). Above is a winged sun-disk which encloses five columns of text naming the gods and the deceased lady. Djedbastetiusankh, who stands on the right in adoration of Ra-Horakhty, a serpent, and Osiris. The surface of the stela has worn away in several places and two large holes have been drilled in the base for mounting in recent times. The background of the stela is buff. The sky-sign is blue. The standards have yellow poles with red and blue bands and blue hangings with red tips. Only the lower part of the top of the standard of the West remains, and this appears to have been blue. The sun-disk is red with yellow uraei and upper wings. The other wings appear to be green, or possibly blue now faded to green, with black lines and red edges. The female figure has a green body, blue wig, black eye, green and white cone, red dress with a blue fringe, yellow jewellery, and red and yellow cloths in her hand. Ra-Horakhty has a red disk, blue wig, white face with black eye, yellow shoulder, green black-lined collar, green hands and sceptre, and red body. The serpent is green with a blue beard, now mostly faded green, and a white and red cone. Osiris has a yellow crown with blue feathers, one now faded green, black uraeus, green face with black features and blue beard, yellow shoulder with red at the back, green black-lined collar, green hands and sceptre, and red body. The hieroglyphs are black on a yellow background between blue lines. The sides and back are plastered.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela depicting Djedbastetiusankh: this small round-topped stela consists of one scene and a line of text below. The scene is bordered at the top by a curved sky-sign and on each side by the standards of the West (on the left) and presumably of the East (on the right). Above is a winged sun-disk which encloses five columns of text naming the gods and the deceased lady. Djedbastetiusankh, who stands on the right in adoration of Ra-Horakhty, a serpent, and Osiris. The surface of the stela has worn away in several places and two large holes have been drilled in the base for mounting in recent times. The background of the stela is buff. The sky-sign is blue. The standards have yellow poles with red and blue bands and blue hangings with red tips. Only the lower part of the top of the standard of the West remains, and this appears to have been blue. The sun-disk is red with yellow uraei and upper wings. The other wings appear to be green, or possibly blue now faded to green, with black lines and red edges. The female figure has a green body, blue wig, black eye, green and white cone, red dress with a blue fringe, yellow jewellery, and red and yellow cloths in her hand. Ra-Horakhty has a red disk, blue wig, white face with black eye, yellow shoulder, green black-lined collar, green hands and sceptre, and red body. The serpent is green with a blue beard, now mostly faded green, and a white and red cone. Osiris has a yellow crown with blue feathers, one now faded green, black uraeus, green face with black features and blue beard, yellow shoulder with red at the back, green black-lined collar, green hands and sceptre, and red body. The hieroglyphs are black on a yellow background between blue lines. The sides and back are plastered.

description.value: Sycamore fig wood stela of Duwenespanefer: there are three sections on this round-topped stela. At the top is a sun-disk with uraei. The top and middle sections are divided by a multi-coloured border. The scene in the middle is placed below a sky-sign. The deceased stands on the right in adoration of Ra-Horakhty and Isis. Between him and the divinities is an altar on which rests a water-pot cooled by a lotus-flower. There are five lines of text below, which contain a prayer on behalf of Duwenespanefer, son of P?-d?-Ws?r. There are several gouges on the surface of the stela and the colour of blue has faded. Otherwise the stela is fairly well preserved. The background to the top and middle sections is grey. There is a curved yellow border at the top. The disk is red with yellow uraei with blue heads. The hieroglyphs on each side of it are blue, red, and yellow. There is a multi-coloured border consisting of blue, yellow, and red rectangles separated by two white and one black stripe, all edged in blue. In the middle section the sky-sign is blue. The human has a red body, yellow kilt, white collar, chest-strap, and eye. Ra-Horakhty has a red disk and body, white face, blue wig and sceptre, and yellow shoulder. Isis has a yellow body, red dress, blue wig and head-dress, and red fillet, and apparently white or grey face, now faded. She carries a red and a blue cloth. The altar is blue with a yellow top, the pot blue and the lotus blue with a yellow base and white patches. Two columns for hieroglyphs, which were never inscribed, are yellow with blue dividing lines. The hieroglyphs in the lower section are black on alternatively white and yellow backgrounds. The last line is discoloured to brown. There are traces of plaster on the sides and back which is heavily pitted.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela of Hathat: this stela was originally designed in the form of a doorway, but the attached lintel and jambs have been lost. Only the central stela remains, divided into four registers. At the top is a winged sun-disk with uraei between which is a scarab beetle. On either side of it is  an 'wedjat'-eye. The second section consists of a 'kheker'-frieze. In the third register below a sky the deceased Hathat stands on the right in adoration before an altar on which rests a water-pot cooled by a lotus. Behind it stand Ra-Horakhty, a winged Isis enclosing an 'wedjat'-eye above a basket, and the four sons of Horus. In the fourth register were apparently three lines of text with a prayer on behalf of the scribe of the God's Adorer Hathat, son of the possibly like-titled ?d-Mn?w-?w(.f) ?n?. The lintel and jambs of the original stela have been lost, but the holes in which they were fitted remain, as does the pink border around them. The inner stela is much worn and cracked in places. The background of the stela is white and the outer edge and sections are bordered by red, orange, green, and possibly white rectangles separated by one black and two white stripes. The disk at the top is red and the uraei pink. The wings are mostly destroyed, but appear to have had a green upper edge and red edges between the divisions, the colour of which has faded. The beetle is black and the eyes are apparently blue with black pupils. The frieze is green with red ties. In the third register the sky was blue. The body of the deceased is red, wig black and kilt white. The altar and pot are outlined in black, but the original colour, if any, has faded. The lotus is green. Ra-Horakhty has a green body, pink collar, red hands, green sceptre, white face outlined in black, and red disk with black uraeus. Isis has a green body and red dress. The colour on her head-dress has faded so only a black outline remains. Patches of red remain on the left wing and green edged in red on the right wing. The feather on the left wing is green. The eye appears to be black or blue and the basket is green. When preserved, the bodies of the four sons of Horus are green, collars pink and sceptres black. Imsety has a red face and black beard, Hapy a red face, and Duamutef a black face, while that of Qebhsenuef is not preserved. The hieroglyphs here and in the text below are black but are not well preserved.

description.value: Sycomore fig wood stela of Tjentwawaru: this round-topped stela is divided into three registers. At the top is a curved sky-sign beneath which are a winged sun-disk and a line of text. In the second register the lady ?nt-w?-w?-rw stands on the right with her arms raised in adoration before an altar on which rests a water-pot cooled by a lotus-flower. Above are four columns of text of which only three are inscribed. Behind the altar stand Ra-Horakhty, Atum, Isis, and Nephthys. Six lines of text in the third register contain a prayer to Ra-Horakhty, Atum, and Ptah-Sokar-Osiris on behalf of the lady Tadibastet, daughter of    ?d-Hr and the lady T?-w?-w?-rw. The stela has cracked into three parts along the lines of the three planks of wood which compose it and has been badly repaired. The right-hand section is not aligned correctly with the other two. The surface is cracked in places and damaged along the edges. The background of the stela is buff-white. The sky at the top is blue. The disk is red with yellow uraei whose heads are blue. The upper wings are black outlined on white with a blue upper edge; the middle are white with red lines and black dots; and the lower are green edged in black with white tips and a lower red edge. The hieroglyphs are black. The scene in the second register is surrounded by a border  of red,  blue,  yellow, and green rectangles separated by one black and two white stripes all edged in blue. There is a white strip at the top of the scene and a blue sky from which blue dividing lines separate the black columns of text on a white background. The female figure has a green body, red dress, yellow collar, and blue wig. The altar is yellow, and the pot blue. The lotus has a dark green stem, yellow base, green leaves, and blue flowers. The gods have green bodies, red hands, yellow collars, blue wigs, dark green sceptres, and red disks with black uraei. The face of Ra-Horakhty is white with black features, while that of Atum is red with a black beard. The goddesses have green bodies, red dresses, yellow-blue wigs, and hold red cloths. The head-dress of Isis is blue, while that of Nephthys is white with a red corner, edged in blue, and a green basket on top. The text in the third register is black between blue dividing lines. The back and sides were plastered.

description.value: Painted sycomore fig wood stela: there are four registers on this round-topped stela. In the upper register is a winged sun-disk whose uraei enclose a scarab beetle. On either side of the uraei is a recumbent jackal holding a sceptre. In the second register below a sky sit Ra-Horakhty, Atum, and four other deities with disks upon their heads, of which the first two and last are male, but the second to last may be lion-headed and so possibly representing Geb, Shu, Tefnut, and another. In the third register the deceased stands on the right with his arms raised in adoration before an altar on which rest offerings covered by a lotus-flower.   Behind it stand Osiris, Horus, Isis, Nephthys, and a fifth deity all in mummiform guise. The figure of the last is faded. There are three lines of indistinct text in the last register with a prayer to Osiris and Isis for the deceased. The stela is cracked at the top and badly worn on its surface which has been applied directly to the wood. The text is nearly effaced. The stela is bordered on three sides and between registers by a band of blue, white, and red rectangles edged in black. The background of the stela was white. The disk is red with blue upper wings, red-striped middle wings, and green lower wings with black tips. The uraei and beetle are blue with blue and red decoration around them. The jackals are black with red sceptres and sashes and blue and red flags. In the second register the sky is blue. The deities have red bodies, green faces apart from Ra-Horakhty's, which is white with black features, blue wigs and feathers, and red disks apart from Atum whose crown is red and white. In the third register the deceased has a red body, blue wig, and white kilt edged in black. The altar is blue with  red  and  blue  offerings  and  a  red and  blue lotus-flower. The deities have red bodies, green collars, blue wigs, green faces and hands apart from Horus whose face is white with black features, and blue aprons. Osiris has a white crown with blue feathers and a black sceptre. Horus has a red and white crown and black sceptre. The last three carry red cloths and the head-dresses of the first two of them, Isis and Nephthys, are red and blue. The hieroglyphs are black between red lines.

description.value: Limestone stela of Raweben: on the upper part of this round-topped stela appear representations in sunk relief accompanied by incised texts. Ra-Horakhty is seated on a throne on the left beneath a single-winged disk and before an altar on which rests a water-pot cooled by a lotus-flower. A figure on the right stands with raised arms in one of which he holds an offering. The text above him gives the name of ?n-m-?ps.f, while two vertical lines on each side of the figures name Raweben and his son R?-ms. Three horizontal lines of text incised below the scene contain an invocation to Ra-Horakhty on behalf of the workman Raweben. A portion of the surface of the upper part of the stela is raised due to the unevenness of the stone. Traces of the original colour remain. The hieroglyphs were black with red lines between the columns. Traces of blue can be seen on the border of the stela. The bodies, pleats of the kilts and the sun-disk on the head of Ra-Horakhty are red, while the wig and individual features on the face of the standing figure are black. There are traces of blue and red on the throne, while the stem of the lotus is red and the altar edged in red.

description.value: Limestone stela of Paneb: a round-topped  stela carrying two registers with representations carved in shallow sunk relief accompanied by texts which are simply incised. In the upper register the chief workman Paneb kneels on the left in adoration of the goddess Meresger, who is depicted in human form with a serpent's head, seated on a throne on the right. In the lower register Paneb's sons, the workman ??-p?ty and Hd-n?t kneel with arms raised in worship. description.value: Limestone stela of Iy....: a fragmentary round-topped stela bearing on its surface the remains of two registers. The figures are in sunk relief and the texts are incised. The goddess Sekhmet is seated on a throne on the left of the upper register. In front of her stands an altar on which sits a water-pot cooled by a lotus-blossom. A male figure, mostly obliterated, kneels on the right in adoration. He is identified as a workman from Deir el-Medina, but the name is damaged and only Iy ... can be read with certainty. The traces do not appear to suit any known name from Deir el-Medina. Only the upper part of the lower register is preserved. The head of a figure, facing right and apparently kneeling in adoration, appears in the centre, but the object of his devotion on the right is not clearly preserved. Four short columns of text above the head apparently give the name of the father of the figure in the upper register. The stela is in a poor state of preservation. Most of the lower portion is lost and the surface of the remainder is badly broken and worn away. The surface is discoloured by areas of black which may be traces of fire.

description.value: Limestone stela of Amenmose: a round-topped stela divided into two registers with figures in sunk relief and incised texts. In the upper register the workman Amenmose stands on the right with his arms raised in adoration of the goddesses Taweret, Nekhbet and Hathor who are seated on thrones on the left. In front of them stands an altar on which rests a water-pot cooled by a lotus-flower. In the lower register six female figures stand facing left with one arm raised in adoration and the other holding a lotus-blossum or other offering. They are named as the lady of the house, M??y-[?b], the lady of the house, ?nwt-w?bw, whose relationship to the preceding is lost, her daughter Nfrt-Stt, her daughter ?st,her daughter [T]?-h?... and a sixth whose name is lost.  The stela is in a poor state of preservation. It is badly pitted and worn, and the plaster used to smooth the surface has gone yellow, cracked and flaked away in some places. There are no traces of colour.

description.value: White limestone false-door of Behenu: with a heavy undecorated cavetto-comice and torus-moulding. The upper and lower lintels and the four jamb-panels bear offering-texts containing the titles and dignities of Behenu. At the bottom of each vertical line of text is a standing figure of the lady. These figures and the texts are carved in sunk relief. The rectangular panel above the doorway carries a representation of Behenu seated at an offering-table smelling a pot of ointment; piled offerings are shown beyond the table and a short text at the top contains Behenu's name and an abbreviated list of offerings. The quality of the carving of the whole is moderately good. There is damage along the cuts that were made when the slab was divided into four pieces for easy transport. No colour is preserved.

description.value: Limestone stela of Amenemipet: there are two registers on this round-topped stela with incised texts and scenes in sunk relief. In the upper register Amenemipet, undoubtedly a necropolis-workman, stands in adoration on the right holding up an offering to Amun-Ra, Mut and the deified Amenhotep I who are enthroned on the left behind an altar heaped with offerings. The second register is badly damaged with only parts of four columns of text still extant. Only the upper part of this stela is preserved, and this is severely damaged along the upper edge. There is a thick black line along the edges of the stela possibly due to a mounting in the nineteenth century.

description.value: Limestone stela of Nebnefer: a round-topped stela depicting Amun-Ra seated on a throne on the left being worshipped by the workman Nebnefer who stands on the right. It appears that Nebnefer originally held a brazier and a flower but these were later erased, possibly because the figure of the god and man were found to be too close together. Six columns of text appear at the top of the stela. Both figures and text are painted. This stela is well preserved apart from some areas of the text which have worn away. There are slight cracks on the surface of the stone. Most of the colour has survived. The background of the stela is white with a black border at the bottom edge and a blue-green border along the sides and top edge. The hieroglyphs are black between red borders. The figure of Nebnufer is outlined in grey with a red body, black wig and facial features, blue jewellery and white kilt. Amun-Ra is painted dark green over a blue base with black facial features. He wears a white collar and white robe with red dots. His crown was reddish-brown, now mostly worn away, and his plumes were outlined in black and white and composed of red, blue and white blotches of colour. The throne is painted in sections of red, white and blue-green.
